title: For Sale:  Colt 1877 Lightning
postcontent:
Colt 1877 Lightning .38 cal.  5 inch barrel.  Manufactured prior to Dec 31 1898.  Good condition.  Some finish remains but the weapon mostly has a nice patina indicative of its age.  No rust pitting.   All matching numbers and excellent working order. The actions of these weapons are quite intricate and it is rare to find a working example with such tight lock up.  The bore is dark but rifling is still quite strong.  The barrel has the correct two line, block letter address.  Its faint but if you squint real hard you can see it.  There are wrench marks on the top and bottom of the barrel so this may have been a replacement or at least some attempt at removal.  Its obvious from looking at the ejector that it has been in place for quite some time. Also noteworthy is the original bronze spring for the ejector.  The hard rubber grips are intact, worn smooth in places, but they fit well with no chips or cracks.

The Lightning was the first double action revolver Colt produced.  166,000 pieces were made from 1877 to 1910.  It is earning favor more and more with collectors due to its similarity in appearance to the Single Action Army and the distinctive bird’s head grip.  Billy the Kid had one of these Lightnings with him the night Pat Garret shot him down. John Wesley Hardin was known to carry the larger .41 cal version.  This is an excellent way to collect a genuine piece of old west history at a fraction of the cost of an original 1st generation Colt SAA or Winchester rifle.  $850

Additional pictures available at http://s1322.photobucket.com/albums/u563/mope34/Colt/M1877%20Lightning/

title: For Sale:  686 Onyx Shotgun
location: Upper St. Pete, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
26" OU Barrels
3" Magnum Chambers
Automatic Ejectors
First Barrel Selector on Safety
First shot inertia selector for second shot 


The first Onyx - as the name suggests - had completely black metalwork. The action is machined from a solid block of steel with no protrusions through the bottom of the action. The barrels hinge into the action on stub pins or trunnions in each side of the action wall, and lock up is achieved by a U-bolt protruding through the action face. These engage in corresponding holes in the breech face of the barrels. The action walls also have cut outs that the barrel fences engage with, thereby producing a very strong closure.

Woodwork is fairly plain yet functional with this gun. The wood has been treated to a thick gloss polyurethane type finish. The traditional-looking chequering is certainly machine cut but in spite of that the points and diamonds are very neatly cut. In fact they're extremely precise. The stock is finished with a black rubber recoil pad of about 3/4in thickness, which feels comfortable and does help soften the recoil when heavier cartridges are used in the gun.

title: For Trade:  Type 53 and 91/30 Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
I'm not in a hurry to get rid of these rifles but I am curious to see what kinds of offers I might get. 

(If I sold both the Type 53 and 91/30 I have 100 rounds of 174 grain Silver Bear FMJ ammo)

The Chinese Type 53 Carbine is a Warsaw pact M44 Mosin Nagant Clone. It's been sporterized and is rough on the outside (though nowhere near as bad as the ones people have been ordering from magazines lately), but it's internal parts are 100% (I replaced the seer spring) and the barrel is surprisingly clean for it's age. It mics around .3095 like some of the Finnish Mosins meant to shoot 54R rounds (not to be confused with the 53r Finnish models with a .3084 bore). The barrel is free-floated and the stock needs some finishing touches but is in perfect shape to pillar and glassbed so as to finalize it's sporting potential. 

The 91/30 Mosin Nagant is a 1939 Izhevsk rifle which was refurbished after WWII. Unfortunately it does not have the oiler kit or the bayonet but does have the cleaning rod. The Wood is stellar for a rifle of it's age, there is no rust -anywhere- on this gun, the trigger/sear is in perfect condition and the bolt, magazine/floorplate, and any other parts not connected to the barrel and reciever were all replaced and are in immaculate shape. The barrel seems to mic around .312 but I would suggest slugging it to get a more proper reading on both the lands and the grooves.

I have pictures of both so feel free to ask. If you would be interested in a glass/pillar bedding job on the Type 53 or for me to do so for one of your rifles you can inquire and I could try to set something up.

title: For Sale:  Sig Mauser M2 .40 s&w pistol, new
postcontent:
The Mauser M2 is a Mauser branded handgun which is offered in the United States by Sig Sauer. It is a self-loading double-action pistol offered in .45 ACP initially, and later in .40 S&W and .357 SIG. The Mauser M2 is dimensionally similar to the SIG P229 pistol, also manufactured by Sig Sauer. Unlike most SIGs, it utilizes a rotating barrel like a Beretta. It's also striker-fired, like a Glock pistol.
Mauser is a German arms manufacturer 
The M2 by Mauser could arguably be called "the safest handgun on the market today". Several safety features are integrated into the M2's design. The pistol features a loaded chamber indicator on top of the slide, which provides a visual indication that a round is present in the firing chamber. The pistol's magazine disconnect is designed to prevent the. pistol from being fired with the magazine removed from the pistol, even if a live round remains in the chamber. The pistol is equipped with an automatic firing pin safety that will not release the firing pin unless the trigger has been pulled. A disconnector prevents out of battery firing. The double-action only fire control system (in conjunction with the striker firing system) holds the striker at half cock which will not fire the cartridge should it be accidentally released. The manual external safety, located on the back of the slide, allows the owner to quickly observe if the handgun in is the safe mode while in the holster and can be quickly operated with the shooting hand.

Mauser M2 Technical Specifications:
Mechanical rotary-action bolt; Striker-fired (no hammer); Double-action only semiautomatic pistol; loaded chamber indicator, magazine safety disconnect, manual safety,  .40 S&W caliber.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Bersa 383-A .380 acp
postcontent:
This is sort of a rare bird,only made from 1986  to 1988 and is the precurser to the modern Bersa Thunder .380.

It is made of steel and wood-no alloy or polymer.Very similar feel and looks of a PPK or Makarov.

Single and double action with decocker/safety.Small enough for a ccw.

I think it is in 90% condition due to some small and light scratches on the front of the slide and trigger guard.

Has not been fired much and the bore is excellent with sharp rifiling.

Comes with Tagua I.W.B. holster and 25 rounds ammo.



I will consider firearms trades.



My pistol was imported by RSA Enterprises:

The Model 383DA was the double-action replacement for the single-action Model 383, retaining the latter's 'combat' trigger guard (providing a forward finger rest), and the swing-down disassembly lever on the right side of the frame, but adopting a new tang trigger and a different disconnector bar. The earlier trigger safety was discarded, and the magazine catch moved to the vacated location. The magazine disconnect safety remains, and the slide-mounted hammer safety of the second-generation pistols is reinstated. Some Model 383DA pistols are rollmarked "Model 383-A", and this phenomenon seems restricted to units imported to the U.S. by RSA Enterprises, who would later become the main US importer for all Bersa products. However, at the time, the main importer was K-MAX International. The Model 383DA was in production from 1986 to 1988, after which Bersa's fifth generation of pistols was launched and the Model 83 claimed its place as Bersa's current production, single-stack .380 ACP pistol.
